(42, 22, 71, 40, 26, 65, 66, 'What need we any further witness?', 'Witnesses and Blasphemy', 'Both passages emphasize the need for witnesses in a trial context. They highlight the conclusion that the statements made by Jesus are sufficient for a verdict of guilt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 71, 41, 14, 63, 64, NULL, 'Condemnation of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the finality of the trial against Jesus, as they both state, ''What need we any further witnesses?'' This connection highlights the moment of judgment where the authorities decide to condemn him based on their own testimony.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 1, 40, 27, 1, 2, 'led him unto Pilate', 'Jesus'' Delivery to Pilate', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leading Jesus to Pilate. The SOURCE verse states that the multitude led him to Pilate, while the TARGET passage describes the chief priests and elders delivering him to the same governor.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 1, 40, 27, 11, 14, 'led him unto Pilate', 'Jesus Before Pilate', 'This connection highlights the moment when Jesus is presented to Pilate, as indicated in both passages. Luke 23:1 mentions the multitude leading Jesus to Pilate, while Matthew 27:11 describes Jesus standing before the governor, emphasizing the trial''s setting.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 1, 41, 15, 1, 5, 'led him unto Pilate', 'Connection of Jesus'' Trial', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leading Jesus to Pilate. The SOURCE verse mentions the multitude leading him, while the TARGET passage describes the chief priests and council delivering him to Pilate.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 1, 42, 22, 66, 66, 'led him', 'Connection of Leading Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leading Jesus. In Luke 22:66, he is led into the council, while in Luke 23:1, he is led to Pilate, indicating a continuous journey through the legal proceedings against him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 1, 43, 18, 28, 38, 'led him unto Pilate', 'Jesus'' Delivery to Pilate', 'This connection highlights the act of leading Jesus to Pilate, as seen in both passages. Luke 23:1 states that the multitude led Jesus to Pilate, while John 18:28 describes the same event, emphasizing the transition from Jewish authority to Roman judgment.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 44, 17, 6, 7, 'saying that he himself is Christ a King', 'Accusations Against Jesus and Followers', 'This connection highlights the accusations made against Jesus and his followers regarding their claims of kingship. Both passages emphasize the phrase ''another king'' and the idea of opposing Caesar''s decrees.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 42, 23, 14, 14, 'perverting the nation', 'Accusations of Perverting the People', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of perverting the people. In Luke 23:2, the accusers claim Jesus is ''perverting the nation,'' while in Luke 23:14, Pilate reiterates that he has found no fault in this man who is accused of ''perverteth the people.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 43, 19, 12, 12, 'saying that he himself is Christ a King', 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation that Jesus claimed to be a king, which was seen as a challenge to Caesar''s authority. This connection highlights the political implications of Jesus'' identity as ''Christ a King'' and the resulting pressure from the Jewish leaders.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 11, 21, 10, 13, 'perverting the nation', 'Accusations Against the Innocent', 'Both passages emphasize false accusations leading to unjust condemnation. In Luke, Jesus is accused of perverting the nation, while in 1 Kings, Naboth is falsely charged with blasphemy. This connection highlights the theme of wrongful testimony against the innocent.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 19, 62, 4, 4, 'perverting the nation', 'Accusation and Deception Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of false accusations and deceit. In Luke 23:2, Jesus is accused of perverting the nation, while Psalms 62:4 speaks of those who consult to cast down another with lies.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 24, 20, 10, 10, 'perverting the nation', 'Accusation and Defamation', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusation and defamation present in both passages. In Luke, Jesus is accused of perverting the nation, while in Jeremiah, the speaker experiences defamation and watchfulness from others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 2, 24, 38, 4, 4, NULL, 'Accusations Against Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusations against individuals perceived as threats to authority. Both passages depict characters being accused of undermining the welfare and stability of their respective communities.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 43, 1, 49, 49, 'King of the Jews', 'Connection of Kingship in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of kingship, with Pilate questioning Jesus about being ''the King of the Jews'' and Nathanael declaring Him ''the King of Israel.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' royal identity in different contexts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 54, 6, 13, 13, 'Art thou the King of the Jews?', 'Connection of Jesus'' Kingship', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' identity as ''King of the Jews'' in Luke, which is affirmed in 1 Timothy where He is noted for His confession before Pilate. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' royal status and His testimony during His trial.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 41, 15, 2, 2, 'Art thou the King of the Jews?', 'Pilate''s Question to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s inquiry about Jesus'' identity as the King of the Jews. The responses in both verses are identical, highlighting a direct textual parallel.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 42, 1, 32, 33, 'Art thou the King of the Jews?', 'Connection of Kingship Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingship in both passages. In Luke 23:3, Pilate questions Jesus about being the King of the Jews, while Luke 1:32-33 proclaims Jesus'' royal lineage and eternal reign.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 42, 22, 70, 70, 'Thou sayest it', 'Jesus'' Identity Affirmation', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' acknowledgment of his identity. In Luke 22:70, he affirms being the Son of God, while in Luke 23:3, he acknowledges being the King of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 40, 27, 11, 11, 'Art thou the King of the Jews?', 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' identity as the King of the Jews. The phrasing of Pilate''s question and Jesus'' response is nearly identical, highlighting a significant moment in the trial narrative.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 3, 41, 15, 18, 18, 'King of the Jews', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Kingship', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus as ''King of the Jews'' in both passages. Pilate''s inquiry in Luke sets the stage for the mocking salute in Mark, emphasizing the theme of Jesus'' royal identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 43, 18, 38, 38, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. The phrase ''I find no fault in this man'' appears in both accounts, highlighting Pilate''s consistent judgment regarding Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 41, 15, 14, 14, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In Luke, Pilate states, ''I find no fault in this man,'' while in Mark, he questions, ''What evil hath he done?'' This connection highlights the consistent theme of Pilate''s recognition of Jesus'' lack of wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 42, 23, 14, 15, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Pilate''s Examination of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s declaration of Jesus'' innocence. In both instances, Pilate states he finds ''no fault in this man,'' reinforcing the theme of Jesus'' lack of guilt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 42, 23, 22, 22, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In Luke 23:4, he states, ''I find no fault in this man,'' and in 23:22, he reiterates, ''I have found no cause of death in him.'' This connection highlights Pilate''s repeated conclusion regarding Jesus'' lack of wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 58, 7, 26, 26, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Innocence of Christ', 'This connection highlights the innocence of Jesus as noted by Pilate, who found ''no fault in this man.'' Similarly, Hebrews describes Jesus as ''holy, harmless, undefiled,'' emphasizing His purity and separation from sin.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 60, 1, 19, 19, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Innocence of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s purity and innocence. Pilate''s declaration of finding ''no fault'' in Jesus parallels the description of Christ as a ''lamb without blemish and without spot.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 4, 60, 2, 22, 22, 'I find no fault in this man', 'Innocence of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' innocence. Both passages emphasize that he did no sin and was found without fault.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 5, 41, 1, 14, 14, 'beginning from Galilee', 'Jesus'' Ministry in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' activity in Galilee, highlighting the geographical focus of His ministry. The mention of ''Galilee'' in both contexts connects the beginning of Jesus'' preaching to the accusations made against Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
